>>180101977

Well if you look at a Saturn V, a huge portion of that rocket is just wasted getting the payload to orbit. So what if we built a cargo delivery device that could then land back on Earth, thus saving us the cost of having to build an entire rocket from the ground up every time we wanted to put something in orbit?

Two problems. First, you're now spending a massive percentage of your potential payload on putting your reusable vehicle into space. That vehicle comes back to you but every kilogram of it is wasted cargo potential. Plus you have to use even more fuel to get the thing into orbit. The Shuttle had less cargo capacity than the Saturn V, which sounds insane, but that's because the Saturn V could spend it's entire cargo capacity on, well, cargo.

The second problem is the reason behind two Shuttles crashing. Single use vehicles may be wasteful, but they're a fuck load safer. That's because putting something into orbit puts it through a ton of stress. You're talking massive G forces that cause everything to shake like mad. Then you have re-entry, where your vehicle has to plunge through the atmosphere hoping that your heat shield holds against temperatures that rival the surface of the sun. Putting a vehicle through that multiple times is going to cause some serious cumulative damage. Frankly it's a miracle more of them didn't blow up.

So why keep using them? Because the US was locked into producing them and it would have been a gigantic loss of face to back down and say "Well actually we fucked up, these vehicles are a disaster". Better to just keep using them and praying they didn't break. Which didn't entirely work out.

his conversation isn't difficult because of The Architect's verbosity--we understood the general gist of what he said the first time we heard it, even if it sounded like there was somehow more to it. It's difficult because it's the first time it's revealed to us (and Neo) that, not only has humanity already lost to the machines, we lost a long time ago, and all the schemes and plans our cast of heroes have been busy dreaming up are completely, utterly futile.

It's a credit to Neo, that in the face of this nutshot of a revelation (possibly one even worse than learning about the Matrix in the first place) he keeps his cool and realizes, as the previous Ones failed to do, that returning to the Source and allowing "humanity" to be kept in darkness and bondage is the greater evil. The Architect tried to trick him into thinking that humanity's extinction was somehow his responsibility. The only choice he is actually making is whether or not to give up humanity's freedom to choose.

Neo chooses... choice. It's the only consistent conclusion. The Architect chides him for false hope, but as The Oracle remarks later, he's incapable of seeing beyond the goals he's been programmed for. It's certainly Neo's hope that he can save Trinity, but that's not what's driving his decision here

/tv/ is not interested in discussing artistic and technical elements or even plain narrative structures.This is no cinematography and movie making board. /tv/ uses media coverage to discuss social and political issues.
Also if you are just starting out you may want to consider Davinci Resolve. I`ve used Final Cut, Premiere and AVID and i can tell you the only reason to use those is because studios are slow (or rather unwilling) on actualizing their pipelines.
Final Cut became pretty much a toy after 7pro and many of the features that made it a professional choice are gone.
AVID kept it professional and robust and i can`t deny stability is key but if you ask me it`s kind of outdated the moment Adobe came up with the dynamic link thing. Being able to quickly jump from editing to audio and video post is the future, was the future.
Resolve came up with a better solution; tabs. It integrates most of what you need in a single application. It has the best color correction tools on the market and fusion is node based so learning on it make learning some specialized tools like nuke easier. Now, i wouldn`t be a good shill if i wouldn`t mention there is a free version would i? well there is one. You should test it out. The full soft is not very expensive either. 300 dollars is a steal and unlike adobe subscription method it`s a one time thing, plus you get access to every single update for free.
Granted the community is not as big yet so learning resources are limited and pipelines have yet to fully adopt it but small and mid studios will probably do so eventually because of everything i just mentioned.

>>180097730
It really depends on what you're interested in
You could look at bandai which make gundam kits and also star wars kits
All you need to assemble these is some nice sprue cutters and a hobby knife, no glue required, so if you're just looking to get a taste you might want to start there
You can get a $20 HG gundam kit which you can finish in an afternoon or you can go with a PG gundam kit which might take a few weeks
Not needing glue is nice because you can just sit in your room and assemble the model, if you want to glue you need good ventilation unless you want to damage your brain

If you're interested in the wider hobby, generally these are supposed to be painted and if you didn't you'd end up with a mono colour model that wasn't very interesting
If you're interested in tanks you could buy a tamiya 1/48 scale kit, these are fairly cheap relative to the rest of the hobby, they fit together like a dream and are not too fiddly or complicated but are very detailed
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JN-EI0TgoBE
Go have a look at this video to see what the process is like

I know, I've both read the book and seen the film (the one and only film, that is).
The book was genuinely fascinating from a hard sci-fi perspective, felt like the must authentic sci-fi story I've ever experienced in terms of going so deeply into the concepts and phenomena that the book is about, it felt like this stuff really happened in our world. It's also extraordinarily dry from a character perspective, however (not sure whether this was intentional or not).
Tarkovsky's film is pretty weak if you're looking for a compelling sci-fi story (Stalker is superior in that regard) but in terms of being an incredibly atmospheric and enthralling mystery film with ultra-comfy retro futurism aesthetics (pretty much the film that made me love that aesthetic) it's a masterpiece.

Was really into The Godfather back then so you can imagine how terrified I was. At the end of the movie you and the other characters are sitting in a room talking about the movie for a while until you exit the blue door and wake up (NOT the white door, never the white door remember!). Almost like you are all actors but the characters aren't totally aware of it. For example I had a word with Vito Corleone/Marlon Brando and he told me that the heart attack in his death scene was actually quite painful and not just pretending. This stage by the way is the only time you can bring up that they are in a movie, if you try to tell them during the actual movie they will become hostile very quickly and can act way out of character. I once got shanked by Gandalf when I told him he was in a movie because I was curious what he would do. When I later in the room asked him what was up with that he did not remember anything. All in all it has been a positive influence in my life, meeting all these strange characters and talking with them and having them share their wisdom with me. I recommend you keep at it, it is well worth it.

Comments like this suggests you barely, if at all, understand the serial tv medium. Serial television veers towards the absurd or caricaturesque almost inherently by virtue of its form, owing to the fact that serial television is typically crafted to be long running, and so the injection of motorcycle club (MC) culture into the narrative template established by Hamlet (arguably the greatest play in the Western canon) winds up being perfect and builds tonal metacommentary as it progresses through multi-season arcs and ultimately concludes with the sacrifice and martyrdom of Jackson Teller.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com: In an underappreciated sense, I don't think it's unreasonable at all to say that MC content is the unrecognized equivalent to The Matrix in modern times. Even if it is or was released outside of the linear temporal progression that is such that we would say that film, tv series, or docuseries was released in this year, or that year, or this era such that it might be, it's in returning to these things or appreciating them in the moment that we can appreciate and experience this door into a different level of existence that allows us to interpret and experience the world through the lens that is unmistakably MC content.

>>180105175
There was a litany of Avatar games released in 2009, all with the same name but were different depending on your console.

Ubisoft released three different Avatar games.

PS3/Xbox 360/PC third-person shooter game, this was the AAA fancy game with the Na'vi/RDA branching story where you play as Ryder.

Wii/PSP stealth action game, which uses motion controls on the Wii version where you play a nameless Na'vi warrior.

Nintendo DS top-down action game, which is a ripoff of Legend of Zelda: Phantom Hourglass. You play as Nok, a young Na'vi who has to rescue his clan from the sky people.

And then the Gameloft iOS/Android mobile game where you play as Avatar Ryan Lorenz. This is the game with the Neytiri narration in it. Also, unavailable to download as the game has been delisted on both marketplaces.

I have a MEGA link for the PC game if anyone wants it.
